T1  - The Escalation of Commitment To a Course of Action
AU  - Staw, Barry M.
Y1  - 1981/10/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1981.4285694
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1981.4285694
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 577
EP  - 587
VL  - 6
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - There are many instances in which individuals can become locked into a costly course of action. Because it is often possible for persons who have suffered a setback to recoup their losses through an even greater commitment of resources to the same course of action, a cycle of escalating commitment can be produced. In this paper, I review recent research on the escalation of commitment and try to integrate its complex and often conflicting determinants.
AB  - There are many instances in which individuals can become locked into a costly course of action. Because it is often possible for persons who have suffered a setback to recoup their losses through an even greater commitment of resources to the same course of action, a cycle of escalating commitment can be produced. In this paper, I review recent research on the escalation of commitment and try to integrate its complex and often conflicting determinants.
