TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Assessment Center Process And Content Validity: A Reply to Dreher and Sackett,
AU  - Norton, Steven D.
Y1  - 1981/10/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1981.4285678
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1981.4285678
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 561
EP  - 568
VL  - 6
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The content validity of the managerial assessment center approach is founded on the resemblance of the process as a whole to the job of a manager as a whole. Therefore, the primary threats to the content validity of the assessment center process are poor design and poor implementation, not a lack of sophisticated job analysis or of a close match between job activities and assessment dimensions or exercises. Dreher and Sackett's review of court cases regarding paper-and-pencil tests for police officers and firefighters does not provide a persuasive argument for concluding that managerial assessment center procedures lack content validity.
AB  - The content validity of the managerial assessment center approach is founded on the resemblance of the process as a whole to the job of a manager as a whole. Therefore, the primary threats to the content validity of the assessment center process are poor design and poor implementation, not a lack of sophisticated job analysis or of a close match between job activities and assessment dimensions or exercises. Dreher and Sackett's review of court cases regarding paper-and-pencil tests for police officers and firefighters does not provide a persuasive argument for concluding that managerial assessment center procedures lack content validity.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1981.4285678
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1981.4285678
Y2  - 2026/04/24
